This module contains support to simulate keystrokes.

Procs

proc registerHotKeyEx(self: wWindow; id: int; hotkey: Hotkey): bool {.
    discardable, ...raises: [], tags: [].}

Registers a system wide hotkey. Every time the user presses the hotkey registered here, the window will receive a wEvent_HotKey event. If the user processes wEvent_HotKey event and set a postive result (e.g. event.result = 1), the key will not be blocked.

The difference from wNim/wWindow.registerHotKey() is that this procedure use low-level keyboard hook instead of RegisterHotKey API. So that the system default key combination can be replaced, For example: Win + R.

proc registerHotKeyEx(self: wWindow; id: int; hotkey: string): bool {.inline,
    discardable, ...raises: [], tags: [].}
Registers a system wide hotkey. Accept a hotkey string.

Example:

import wNim/wFrame

proc example() =
  var frame = Frame()
  frame.registerHotKeyEx(0, "Ctrl + Alt + F1")
proc send(text: string; raw = false; window = InvalidWindow; attach = false;
          restoreCapslock = false) {....raises: [NPegException, Exception],
                                     tags: [RootEffect].}
Sends simulated keystrokes to the active window. If raw is true, keys are sent raw. If window is specified, it attempts to keep it active during send(). If attach is true, it attaches input threads when during send(). If restoreCapslock is true, the state of capslock is restored after send().

Example:

import window

proc example() =
  send("#r")
  send("notepad{enter}")
  send("abc{BS 3}def", window=waitAny(window.className == "Notepad"))
  send("!fxn")
proc send(window: Window; text: string) {....raises: [], tags: [].}
Sends a string of characters to a window. This window must process WM_CHAR event, for example: an editor contorl.
